## Section 13: Kubernetes Deployments – Core Concepts
### 1. What is a Deployment?A Deployment is a Kubernetes object that manages a set of identical Pods. It runs a configuration (the "Desired State") and ensures that the actual state of the cluster matches it.Primary Purpose: To scale Pods up or down and to update the version of the code running in those Pods without downtime.Relationship: A Deployment creates and manages a ReplicaSet, which in turn manages the Pods.
### 2. Declarative vs. Imperative UpdatesDeclarative (Best Practice): You update your configuration file (YAML) and run kubectl apply -f <filename>. Kubernetes looks at the difference between the current state and the new file and makes the necessary changes.Imperative: You give the CLI a direct command to change something (e.g., kubectl set image...). While faster for quick fixes, it's harder to track in version control.
### 3. Key Deployment Workflow (Updating Images)When you want to update your application code:Rebuild your Docker image with a new tag (e.g., v2).Push the image to Docker Hub.Update the image property in your Deployment configuration file.Apply the change using kubectl apply.

