## Common Interview Questions & AnswersQ: Why use a Deployment instead of a Pod?"Pods are ephemeral; if they crash, they aren't automatically replaced.
A Deployment provides self-healing and scaling. It ensures the specified number of replicas are always running and handles rolling updates seamlessly.
"Q: How does Kubernetes handle a Deployment update?"By default, it uses a Rolling Update strategy. It spins up a new version of the Pod, waits for it to become healthy, and then terminates an old version. This ensures zero downtime during deployment.
"Q: What is a ClusterIP Service, and why is it used with Deployments?
"While a Deployment manages the Pods, their IP addresses change every time they are recreated. A ClusterIP Service provides a single, stable IP address/port to reach that set of Pods, acting as an internal load balancer.
"Q: What are the limitations of updating a Deployment?"You cannot change certain 'immutable' fields of an existing object without recreating it.
Additionally, if you use the latest tag for Docker images without changing the YAML file, Kubernetes might not realize an update is needed. It is best practice to use unique version tags
